                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>Front left corner of a large, well finished block of compact grey limestone. Broken to the rear, left and right sides in a diagonal break from mid-front to rear left coner. Intact top, bottom, front left. The lower face is finished smooth, like the front; The upper and left side faces are finished, but left rough picked.</p>
                                    <material ana="#material.stone.limestone" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/66.html">limestone</material>
                                    <objectType ana="#object.statue_base" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/57.html" cert="low">statue base</objectType>
                                    <dimensions><!--measurements of Gentili 42 x 48 x 47-->
                                        <height unit="cm">41.8</height>
                                        <width unit="cm">49</width>
                                        <depth unit="cm">46.8</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition ana="#condition.damaged"/>
		    </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>
                                    <p>Three lines of large Greek letters; all are incomplete, but the unjustified left margin suggests a text that was originally centred on the stone</p>
                                    <rs ana="#execution.chiselled" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1">chiselled</rs>
                                	<damage ana="#text_condition.incomplete"/>
			</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><p>Thinly incised broad letters of regular height, without serifs or marked terminations to the strokes. Alpha has straight bar; Beta has closed loops, in the second instance separated from one another. Sigma has parallel top and bottom strokes, the mid-strokes meeting slightly over halfway across.</p>
                                <locus from="line1" to="line3">Line 1-3</locus>
